Abstract
Ferroic domain walls are currently investigated by several state-of-the art techniques in order
to get a better understanding of their distinct, functional properties. Here, Principal Component
Analysis (PCA) of Raman maps is used to study ferroelectric domain walls (DWs) in LiNbO
and ferroelastic DWs in NdGaO
. It is shown that PCA allows to quickly and reliably identify
small Raman peak variations at ferroelectric DWs and that the value of a peak shift can be
deduced - accurately and without
a-priori
- from a first order Taylor expansion of the spectra.
The ability of PCA to separate the contribution of ferroelastic domains and DWs to Raman
spectra is emphasized. More generally, our results provide a novel route for the statistical
analysis of any property mapped across a DW.
